4. List all primitive datatypes in Java. What kind of values do they store?
-->In Java, there are eight primitive data types predefined by the language. These types represent basic values and are stored directly in memory rather
    than as objects. 

    Integer Types (Whole Numbers)
    byte: Stores 8-bit signed integers from -128 to 127. It is useful for saving memory in large arrays.
    short: Stores 16-bit signed integers from -32,768 to 32,767.
    int: Stores 32-bit signed integers from -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647. This is the most common type for whole numbers.
    long: Stores 64-bit signed integers from -9,223,372,036,854,775,808 to 9,223,372,036,854,775,807. Use this when int is not large enough. 

    Floating-Point Types (Decimal Numbers) 
    float: Stores single-precision 32-bit fractional numbers. It is suitable for storing 6 to 7 decimal digits.
    double: Stores double-precision 64-bit fractional numbers. It is suitable for storing 15 to 16 decimal digits and is the default choice for decimals. 

    Other Basic Types
    boolean: Stores only two possible values: true or false. It is primarily used for conditional logic and flags.
    char: Stores a single 16-bit Unicode character. It can represent letters, digits, symbols, or ASCII values.


