      String
      String str = "Hello";
      Array
      int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
      Interface
      Runnable r;
      🔁 Key Points
      Store reference (address), not actual data
      Stored in heap memory
      Can be null
      Created using new keyword (mostly)
      🎯 Simple Understanding
      
      👉 Primitive → stores value
      👉 Reference → stores address of value
      
      📝 Short Exam Answer
      
      A reference data type in Java stores the memory address of an object rather than the actual value. Examples include String, arrays,
      classes, and interfaces.


7. Can primitive datatypes hold null? Can reference datatypes hold null?
-->In Java, whether a data type can hold a null value depends on whether it is a primitive or a reference type. 
    Primitive Data Types: No, primitive data types cannot hold null. According to the Oracle Java Tutorials, the null literal cannot be assigned to
    variables of primitive types. Primitives such as int, boolean, and double must always hold a concrete value, falling back to predefined default 
    values (like 0 or false) if they are uninitialized.

    Reference Data Types: Yes, reference data types can hold null. As explained by W3Schools, reference types (such as String, Array, or any class
    instance) store memory addresses rather than actual data. A value of null indicates that the reference variable does not point to any object 
    in memory. 


