9. Can a variable be declared without assigning a value? What happens if you try to use it?
-->1. Local Variables (Inside a Method)
    If you declare a variable inside a method, it is a local variable. 
    Behavior: Java does not assign default values to local variables.
    What happens if you use it: If you try to use an uninitialized local variable, the compiler will throw a compile-time error stating that the variable might not have been initialized.
    Example:
    java
    void myMethod() {
        int x; // Declared but not assigned
        System.out.println(x); // COMPILE-TIME ERROR: variable x might not have been initialized
    }

    2. Class-Level Variables (Instance or Static)
    Variables declared directly within a class (outside methods) are fields. 
    Behavior: Java automatically assigns a default value to these variables based on their data type.
    What happens if you use it: You can use them immediately without explicit initialization, and the program will run using the default value.
    Common Default Values:
    int, byte, short, long: 0
    float, double: 0.0
    boolean: false
    char: '\u0000' (null character)
    Object References (e.g., String): null




10. Can primitive datatypes be declared inside constructors, static blocks, instance blocks, or non-static methods? Explain.
-->Yes — primitive data types can be declared anywhere inside a class, including constructors, static blocks, instance blocks, and methods in Java.
    
    👉 Because primitives are just normal variables, they follow the same scope rules.
    
    ✅ 1. Inside Constructor
    
    ✔️ Allowed — they act as local variables
    
    class Demo {
        Demo() {
            int x = 10;  // primitive inside constructor
            System.out.println("Constructor value: " + x);
        }
    }
    ✅ 2. Inside Static Block
    
    ✔️ Allowed — used during class loading
    
    class Demo {
        static {
            int x = 20;  // primitive inside static block
            System.out.println("Static block value: " + x);
        }
    }
    ✅ 3. Inside Instance Block
    
    ✔️ Allowed — runs when object is created
    
    class Demo {
        {
            int x = 30;  // primitive inside instance block
            System.out.println("Instance block value: " + x);
        }
    }
    ✅ 4. Inside Non-Static Method
    
    ✔️ Allowed — most common usage
    
    class Demo {
        void display() {
            int x = 40;  // primitive inside method
            System.out.println("Method value: " + x);
        }
    }
    🔥 Important Note
    
    👉 All these variables are local variables, so:
    
    Stored in stack memory
    No default values (must be initialized before use)
    🎯 Final Answer (Exam Ready)
    
    Yes, primitive data types can be declared inside constructors, static blocks, instance blocks, and methods. In all these cases, they behave as
      local variables and must be initialized before use.




11. If you declare all primitive datatypes inside a method and try to print them without initialization, what happens?
-->If you declare primitive datatypes inside a method (as local variables) and attempt to print them without initialization, the program will fail to compile. 
    According to the Java Language Specification, the following happens:
    Compiler Error: The Java compiler will throw a "variable might not have been initialized" error.
    No Default Values: Unlike class-level (instance or static) variables, local variables are not automatically assigned default values like 0 or false.
    Mandatory Initialization: You must explicitly assign a value to a local variable before it is accessed in any operation, including printing
    with System.out.println().
    Safe Declaration: Simply declaring the variables without using them is allowed and will not cause an error; the error only triggers when you try
    to use (read) the uninitialized variable.


12. What happens if you declare a primitive variable with a value larger than its range? Give an example.
-->In Java, if you assign a value larger than the allowed range of a primitive data type, you’ll get a compile-time error (in most direct assignments).
    
    🔹 Case 1: Direct Assignment (Compile-Time Error)
    byte b = 130;   // ❌ Error
    
    👉 Why?
    
    byte range = -128 to 127
    130 is outside the range
    
    ✔️ Result: Compilation fails
    
    🔹 Case 2: With Explicit Casting (Overflow Happens)
    byte b = (byte)130;
    System.out.println(b);
    
    👉 Output:
    
    -126
    ⚠️ Why this happens?
    Java cuts extra bits (overflow)
    It wraps around using 2’s complement
    🔹 Another Example
    int x = (int)2147483648L;
    System.out.println(x);
    
    👉 Output:
    
    -2147483648
    🎯 Key Concept
    
    👉 If value exceeds range:
    
    Without casting → ❌ Compile-time error
    With casting → ⚠️ Overflow (wrong/rotated value)
    🧠 Easy Understanding
    
    Think like a clock ⏰:
    
    Max reached → it starts again from minimum
    👉 This is called overflow
    📝 Short Exam Answer
    
    If a primitive variable is assigned a value beyond its range, Java gives a compile-time error. If explicitly cast, the value overflows 
    and produces an incorrect result due to wrap-around.




13. If you declare a variable with a primitive types, what does JVM do internally? How much memory is allocated?
-->When you declare a variable with a primitive type in Java, the JVM performs specific internal actions depending on where that variable is defined. 
    Internal JVM Actions
    Local Variables: When declared inside a method, the JVM allocates space on the Stack memory. At runtime, each method call creates a new Stack Frame. 
    The JVM reserves a slot in this frame for the primitive variable's actual value, not a pointer.
    Instance Variables: If a primitive is a field within a class, the JVM allocates space for it on the Heap memory as part of the object’s blueprint.
    Memory is allocated the moment the object is created using the new keyword.
    Static Variables: For static primitives, the JVM allocates memory in the Method Area (or Metaspace) during the class loading and linking phase. 



14. Where are primitive variables stored in memory?
-->Primitive variables are stored in different memory locations depending on where they are declared. Their storage is primarily determined by their
    scope and the structure they belong to: 

Stack Memory: Primitive values are stored on the stack when they are declared as local variables within a method or function. This includes method
                parameters. The memory is allocated in a "stack frame" when the method is called and is automatically deallocated once the method
                finishes execution.
Heap Memory: Primitive values are stored on the heap when they are declared as instance variables (fields) of a class or as elements within an array.
                In these cases, the primitive is part of the larger object or array structure that lives on the heap.
Method Area / Static Area: In languages like Java, static primitive variables are typically stored in a specialized section of the
                heap (often referred to as the Method Area or Permanent Generation). They persist for the entire lifetime of the application. 




15. Where are reference variables stored in memory?
-->Reference variables are generally stored in different parts of memory based on their scope and context of declaration: 
    Stack Memory: Local reference variables (declared within a method or function) are stored on the stack. The variable itself holds a memory
    address or "handle" that points to the actual object.
    Heap Memory: Reference variables that are instance fields (member variables of a class) are stored on the heap alongside the object to which
    they belong.
    Method Area / Static Data: Reference variables declared as static (class variables) are typically stored in the Method Area or a specific static 
    data segment within the heap.
    CPU Registers: In highly optimized code, compilers may store local reference variables directly in CPU registers for faster access, avoiding
    memory altogether if the variable's address is never taken. 
    
    Summary of Storage Locations
    Variable Type 	Storage Location	Notes
    Local Variables	Stack	Temporary; exists only during method execution.
    Instance Variables	Heap	Part of the object instance; exists as long as the object does.
    Static Variables	Method Area / Heap	Persistent for the duration of the program or JVM lifecycle.



16. What happens if you assign one reference variable to another?
-->When you assign one reference variable to another (e.g., obj2 = obj1), the following occurs:
    Reference Copying: The memory address (reference) stored in the first variable is copied into the second.
    Shared Object: Both variables now "point" to the same object in memory.
    No Object Duplication: A new object is not created; only a second reference to the existing object is established.
    Shared Modifications: Any changes made to the object through one variable will be reflected when accessing it through the other, as they both 
    refer to the same underlying data.
    Independence of Variables: While they point to the same object, the variables themselves remain independent. If you later reassign one variable
    to a new object or null, the other variable continues to point to the original object.
    Memory Management: The object remains in memory as long as at least one active reference variable points to it. If all references are removed,
    the object becomes eligible for garbage collection. 


