    Underflow: Occurs when a value is smaller than the minimum limit of the data type. It "wraps around" to the maximum value. 


18. What happens if you call a method on a null reference variable?
-->1. Instance Methods
        If the method is an instance method (non-static), the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) will throw a NullPointerException (NPE). 
        Why it happens: Instance methods belong to a specific object. When you use a null reference, there is no actual object in memory for the
                        method to run on.
        Result: The program stops immediately (crashes) unless you use a try-catch block to handle the error
        🔴
        String str = null;
        str.length();   // method call
        🔴 Output:
        Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NullPointerException


        2. Static Methods
        If the method is declared as static, the program will run normally without any exception. 
        
        Why it works: Static methods belong to the class itself, not to an instance (object). Java uses the variable's declared type at compile-time
        to find the method, completely ignoring the fact that the variable's value is null.
        Note: While this works, it is considered bad practice. You should always call static methods using the class name (e.g., ClassName.methodName())
        to avoid confusion. 
            class Test {
                static void display() {
                    System.out.println("Hello");
                }
            }
            
            public class Main {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                    Test t = null;
                    t.display();   // calling static method using null reference
                }
            }
            ✅ Output:
            Hello


