20. Can primitive and reference datatypes be mixed in expressions, like int + Integer? What happens?
-->Yes, primitive (e.g., int) and reference/wrapper types (e.g., Integer) can be mixed in expressions in Java. 
  
    When you mix them, Java uses autounboxing to automatically convert the reference type (Integer) into its corresponding primitive type (int) so that arithmetic operations can be performed. 

    What Happens? (Example: int + Integer)
    Expression: int a = 5; Integer b = 10; int sum = a + b;
    Process: The Java compiler automatically calls the intValue() method on the Integer object (b.intValue()).
    Operation: The operation becomes 5 + 10.
    Result: The result is a primitive int (15).


21. Can a final primitive or reference variable be changed after initialization? What happens?
-->A final variable in Java cannot be reassigned after it has been initialized. However, its behavior differs slightly depending on whether it
    is a primitive or a reference variable. 
    
    1. Primitive Variables
    Can they be changed? No. For primitive types (like int, double, etc.), the variable stores the actual value. Marking it final makes that value a constant.
    What happens? Any attempt to reassign a new value to the variable (e.g., x = 10;) after its initial assignment will result in a compile-time error. 
    
    2. Reference Variables
    Can they be changed? It depends on what you mean by "change":
    The Reference: No. You cannot reassign the variable to point to a different object or null.
    The Object State: Yes. If the object itself is mutable (like an ArrayList or a custom object), you can still modify its internal fields or call methods 
        that change its state.
    Variable Type 	Reassignment (of value/address)	Modification (of internal state)	Result of Reassignment Attempt
    Primitive	Not Allowed	N/A (Primitives have no internal state)	Compile-time error
    Reference	Not Allowed	Allowed (if the object is mutable)	Compile-time error



